<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="71cd6057f09b34426d1aced53249d173" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Standard format<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.88)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12149'>Patrick "CaptCanada" Malboeuf</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 25, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Today, Decipher has announced that all championship level events would be held in the standard format, one where a list of cards (which will be updated as the season goes one) are forbidden. Anyone can look at the changes on www.dgma.com.<br />
<br />
I usually don’t comment on Decipher’s errata and game changing decisions, however I feel that the decision they have just made is far more important, and drastic than issuing any Grima you can possibly think of. This article is dedicated to express my position towards the new standard format.<br />
<br />
First, let us look at the main arguments presented in response to this announcement.<br />
<br />
1. Against: Decipher restricts the player’s freedom by choosing for them what cards they should or shouldn’t play which is the anti-thesis of its regulating function. Once the cards are released and in the hands of the customers, Decipher should accept that the players become actors and that it becomes the referee, or regulating body.<br />
<br />
1. For: Decipher doesn’t restrict the player’s freedom since you are always free to choose what format to play.<br />
<br />
1. Against: While true for local tournaments, any championship level player doesn’t have that choice (Trevor McGreggor’s argument).<br />
<br />
<br />
2. For: It stops the “mega fellowship” (lots of companions, lots of allies from many cultures) from being the best fellowship (Decipher’s argument) and thus encourages diversity.<br />
<br />
2. Against: In theory that is a good argument, but tell me where is this mega fellowship which is superior to every other one Decipher is talking about. Surely, such a superior fellowship would be used at top level tournaments, but in Vegas, what dominated was rohan/gondor, horn, choke or bad beef fellowships (Mike Daulton’s argument).<br />
<br />
2. Against: While those changes are justified by their ability to delete the supremacy of some types of decks or cards, the fact of the matter is that nowhere better than in Vegas was the diversity and the balance of Lotr best demonstrated as huge fellowships were opposed to choking ones, classical shadows opposed to new ones. While I agree that those changes would do good to a unidirectional tournament scene, the Las Vegas premier series’ deck diversity has showed us the depth of Lotr.<br />
<br />
<br />
3. Against: It seems like Decipher just want us to play with crappy cards. They not only eliminate cards which make a particular kind of deck strong or superior, but attack every single card that we judge to be good.<br />
<br />
3. For: Again, we have to remember that this is only true for the championship level tournaments. I myself believe that when you decide to play in the top level circuit and aspire to win, you put behind you the personal or emotive considerations for cards or decks and play with whatever card is legal and allows you to win.<br />
<br />
<br />
In conclusion, I personally think that Decipher’s role, once it has issued cards must be a transparent, or silent one, letting as much possible latitude to the players who have paid for their cards and who have put great amount of time into building solid decks with which they are comfortable and most importantly with which they have fun.<br />
<br />
However, I agree that an unbalanced or unidirectional championship level tournament scene does no good to a game and that it is Decipher’s responsibility to act in order to keep a balanced play environment. I just don’t think that the actual tournament scene is an unbalanced or unidirectional one. Personnally, I came back from Vegas building 4 or 5 completely different kind of decks all of which continue to win against certain types of decks and all of which that are championship level tournament worth. I two was concerned about the predominance of certain kinds of decks going into Vegas, but I was also very pleased that choke/dunland won, in order to show everyone who taught the game was unidirectional wrong. Lord of the Rings, although young is a game with a great depth to it.<br />
<br />
As a championship level player, I am not in favour of the those new changes, but I am not opposed either, for a very simple reason: I do not care for the fact that I like particular cards or that I am used to play certain cards. As far as I’m concerned, those cardboard pieces could have numbers and colours on them and I would still try to do the best that I can to win with what I have in hand.<br />
<br />
So if you are a local tournament player, you still have the choice to play any card you want and I hope you are happy with the fact that Decipher came up with the original idea of the standard format instead or errataing the cards you love.<br />
<br />
And if you’re a championship level player, I humbly suggest you transfer the energies you put in trying to change what you cannot (the luck factor, the game mechanics of Lotr, the changes made by the Decipher staff) to invest them into what you CAN change (your ability to adapt to new game environments, to pull a win even when luck is against you, to be able to play any deck that is necessary for you to win instead on only investing your time on one particular type of deck.).<br />
<br />
So, Decipher has judged that the game environment was too unidirectional and needed change, I don’t agree, but you should see the new bad beef my brother just made, it will kick arses.<br />
<br />
Feel free to agree or disagree, I am open to comments.<br />
<br />
Patrick Malboeuf.<br />
